SIMPLE: execute
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Execute
<hw>Ex"e*cute</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Executed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Executing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>ex⟦eacute⟧cuter</ets>, L. <ets>executus</ets>,
<ets>exsecutus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>exequi</ets> to follow to the end,
pursue; <ets>ex</ets> out + <ets>sequi</ets> to follow. See
<er>Second</er>, <er>Sue</er> to follow up, and cf.
<er>Exequy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To follow out or through to the
end; to carry out into complete effect; to complete; to finish; to
effect; to perform.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why delays⟦br⟧
His hand to <qex>execute</qex> what his decree⟦br⟧
Fixed on this day?</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To complete, as a legal instrument; to perform what
is required to give validity to, as by signing and perhaps sealing and
delivering; <as>as, to <ex>execute</ex> a deed, lease, mortgage, will,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To give effect to; to do what is provided or
required by; to perform the requirements or stipulations of; <as>as, to
<ex>execute</ex> a decree, judgment, writ, or process</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To infect capital punishment on; to put to death in
conformity to a legal sentence; <as>as, to <ex>execute</ex> a
traitor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To put to death illegally; to kill.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>To perform, as a piece of music or
other feat of skill, whether on an instrument or with the voice, or in
any other manner requiring physical activity; <as>as, to
<ex>execute</ex> a difficult part brilliantly; to <ex>execute</ex> a
coup; to <ex>execute</ex> a double play</as>.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To accomplish; effect; fulfill; achieve;
consummate; finish; complete. See <er>Accomplish</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Execute</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Execute
<hw>Ex"e*cute</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To do one's work;
to act one's part or purpose.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Hayward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To perform musically.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Executer</ent>⟦br⟧
